{"id":"2103.11682","submitter":"Risto Paatelainen","authors":"Adrian Dumitru, Heikki M\\\"antysaari and Risto Paatelainen","title":"Color charge correlations in the proton at NLO: beyond geometry based\n  intuition","comments":"11 pages, 10 figures, v3: published version","journal-ref":"Phys.Lett.B 820 (2021)","doi":"10.1016/j.physletb.2021.136560","report-no":"HIP-2021-13/TH","categories":"hep-ph hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Color charge correlators provide fundamental information about the proton\nstructure. In this Letter, we evaluate numerically two-point color charge\ncorrelations in a proton on the light cone including the next-to-leading order\ncorrections due to emission or exchange of a perturbative gluon. The\nnon-perturbative valence quark structure of the proton is modelled in a way\nconsistent with high-$x$ proton structure data. Our results show that the\ncorrelator exhibits startlingly non-trivial behavior at large momentum transfer\nor central impact parameters, and that the color charge correlation depends not\nonly on the impact parameter but also on the relative transverse momentum of\nthe two gluon probes and their relative angle. Furthermore, from the two-point\ncolor charge correlator, we compute the dipole scattering amplitude. Its\nazimuthal dependence differs significantly from a impact parameter dependent\nMcLerran-Venugopalan model based on geometry. Our results also provide initial\nconditions for Balitsky-Kovchegov evolution of the dipole scattering amplitude.\nThese initial conditions depend not only on the impact parameter and dipole\nsize vectors, but also on their relative angle and on the light-cone momentum\nfraction $x$ in the target.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Mar 2021 09:23:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 29 Apr 2021 09:13:23 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 18 Aug 2021 09:22:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-19"}
